@BGRND{{}}
<p>
The @HI{{@EM{{aida}}}} clause expresses the idea of "while" or "during".
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
The subjects in the @HI{{@EM{{aida}}}} clause and the main clause can be the same or different. If they are the same
the subject in the @HI{{@EM{{aida}}}} clause is marked by @HI{{ha}}.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KT{{sumisu}}sanha@KJ{{day^book}}niiru@KJ{{interval^england^word}}wo@KJ{{teach}}eteimashita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Mr. Smith was teaching English <em>(the whole time)</em> he was in Japan.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
If they are different, the subject in the @HI{{@EM{{aida}}}} clause is marked by @HI{{ga}} and not by @HI{{ha}}.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{child^submit^accomplished}}ga@KT{{terebi}}wo@KJ{{see}}teiru@KJ{{interval^private}}ha@KJ{{book}}wo
      @KJ{{read}}ndeimashita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I read a book <em>(the whole time)</em> while my children were watching TV.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
The verb before @HI{{@EM{{aida}}}} is usually either non-past @Vte{{}}@HI{{iru}} or @HI{{iru}} regardless of the
tense of the main clause.
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
If the @HI{{@EM{{aida}}}} clause is followed by @HI{{ni}} then the time span of the main clause
falls within that of the @HI{{@EM{{aida}}}} clause.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{high^bridge}}sanha@KT{{amerika}}niiru@KJ{{interval}}ni@KT{{gorufu}}wo@KJ{{memorize}}emashita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Mr. Takahashi learned golf while he was in America.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
If @HI{{@EM{{aida}}}} is not followed by @HI{{ni}}, the two clauses are expected to cover the same span of time.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{private}}gago@KJ{{meal}}wo@KJ{{eat}}beteiru@KJ{{interval^mountain^rice*field}}sanha@KT{{terebi}}wo
      @KJ{{see}}teimashita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      While I was eating my meal Mr. Yamada was watching TV.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
The clause marked by @HI{{@EM{{aida}}(ni)}} always expresses a continuous state or action.
In the case of @HI{{@EM{{aida}}}}, the following clause also expresses a continuous state or action.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{o@KJ{{mama}}sanga@FG{{@KJ{{daytime^lie*down}}:hirune}}woshiteiru@EM{{aida}},@KJ{{child}}domotachiha@KT{{terebi}}wo@KJ{{see}}teita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      While mother had an afternoon nap, the children watched TV.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
However, in the case of @HI{{@EM{{aida}}}}, the following clause expresses a momentary action or state.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{o@KJ{{mama}}sanga@FG{{@KJ{{daytime^lie*down}}:hirune}}woshiteiru@EM{{aidani}},@KJ{{child}}domotachiha@KJ{{play}}bini@KJ{{exit}}kaketa.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      While mother had an afternoon nap, the children went out to play.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
Note that in this second case, although the playing may or may not continue for some time, the going out (@HI{{@KJ{{exit}}kakeru}}) is a momentary action.
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
The construction A@HI{{to}}B(@HI{{to}})@HI{{no@EM{{aida}}}} means "the space between" or "relationship".

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
